13.body:
first, let's load a DataFrame. # Import data types
from pyspark.sql.types import * # Define the schema, or let it be inferred when loading your data.
schema = StructType( [StructField('instant',IntegerType(), True), StructField('dteday', TimestampType(), True), StructField('season', IntegerType(), True), StructField('yr', IntegerType(), True), StructField('mnth', IntegerType(), True), StructField('holiday', IntegerType(), True), StructField('weekday', IntegerType(), True), StructField('workingday', IntegerType(), True), StructField('weathersit', IntegerType(), True), StructField('temp', DoubleType(), True), StructField('atemp', DoubleType(), True), StructField('hum', DoubleType(), True), StructField('windspeed', DoubleType(), True), StructField('casual', IntegerType(), True), StructField('registered', IntegerType(), True), StructField('cnt', IntegerType(), True) ] ) infer_schema = "false"
file_format = "csv"
delimiter = ","
file = '/databricks-datasets/bikeSharing/data-001/day.csv'
df = spark.read.format(file_format) \ .option("inferShema", infer_schema) \ .option("sep",delimiter) \ .option("header", True) \ .schema(schema) \ .load(file) df.printSchema() Let's see the contents of the dataframe to be written to a delta table: df.show() Run to save this DataFrame as a Delta table to /tmp/delta/ with the name delta-table: try: df.write.format("delta").save("/tmp/delta/delta-table")
except: print("table already exists!") # if it exists, you uncomment the next line and run again to delete it #dbutils.fs.rm('/tmp/delta/delta-table',recurse=True) # let's take a look at the table
display(spark.read.format("delta").load("/tmp/delta/delta-table")) We can run a simple command to make sure that the table is indeed a Delta table: Note: make sure to import delta.tables! from delta.tables import *
DeltaTable.isDeltaTable(spark, "/tmp/delta/delta-table") # True If the table already exists, you can overwrite or append to the table. append will add any non-mathcing records while overwrite replaces all data in the table . df.write.format("delta").mode("append").save("/tmp/delta/delta-table") df.write.format("delta").mode("overwrite").save("/tmp/delta/delta-table") However, you can still not overwrite or append to a table with a different schema . Lets change the schema of the DataFrame and try it! # Define the schema, or let it be inferred when loading your data.
schema = StructType( [StructField('instant',IntegerType(), True), StructField('dteday', TimestampType(), True), #Lets define season as String instead of Int! StructField('season', StringType(), True), StructField('yr', IntegerType(), True), StructField('mnth', IntegerType(), True), StructField('holiday', IntegerType(), True), StructField('weekday', IntegerType(), True), StructField('workingday', IntegerType(), True), StructField('weathersit', IntegerType(), True), StructField('temp', DoubleType(), True), StructField('atemp', DoubleType(), True), StructField('hum', DoubleType(), True), StructField('windspeed', DoubleType(), True), StructField('casual', IntegerType(), True), StructField('registered', IntegerType(), True), StructField('cnt', IntegerType(), True) ] ) infer_schema = "false"
file_format = "csv"
delimiter = ","
file = '/databricks-datasets/bikeSharing/data-001/day.csv'
df_newschema = spark.read.format(file_format) \ .option("inferShema", infer_schema) \ .option("sep",delimiter) \ .option("header", True) \ .schema(schema) \ .load(file) df_newschema.printSchema() df_newschema.write.format("delta").mode("overwrite").save("/tmp/delta/delta-table") This is just standard practice when writing tables. You should not be able to mix and match schemas. However, what happens if we encounter the case where the data capture changes, and a new column is added? #create a new dataframe with an additional column
from pyspark.sql.functions import lit
new_df = df.withColumn("bonus_column", lit(0.3))
new_df.printSchema() new_df.write.format("delta").mode("append").save("/tmp/delta/delta-table") We get schema mismatch again! But this time, it is a Delta specific exception. This is because Delta tables have features called schema enforcement and schema evolution . Schema enforcement (or schema validation ) is a safeguard in Delta Lake that rejects writes to a table that do not match the table's schema. This prevents us from accidentally polluting tables with mistakes or garbage data. In cases of mismatch in schemas, no data is written and an exception is raised letting the user know about the mismatch. Schema evolution allows us to easily change the current table schema to accomodate that data is changing over time. This is commonly used to automatically adapt the schema to include one or more new columns. It can be good to use if you intend to add the columns that were previously rejected due to schema mismatch. More on Schema enforcement and evolution: - https://www.databricks.com/blog/2019/09/24/diving-into-delta-lake-schema-enforcement-evolution.html Let's try writing to the table again, with overwrite mode, and mergeschema = true to enable schema evolution: new_df.write.format("delta").option("mergeSchema","true").mode("overwrite").save("/tmp/delta/delta-table") #display the new table
display(spark.read.format("delta").load("/tmp/delta/delta-table")) Notice that we have just overwritten the data, now with the bonus column. What happens if we configure append instead of overwrite? # for the sake of learning, reset the table to initial dataframe state first
dbutils.fs.rm('/tmp/delta/delta-table',recurse=True)
df.write.format("delta").save("/tmp/delta/delta-table") new_df.write.format("delta").option("mergeSchema","true").mode("append").save("/tmp/delta/delta-table") Now observe the results using display. Scroll down to the earlier entries to see that all of the earlier entries have value null for the new column bonus column. #display the current state of the table
display(spark.read.format("delta").load("/tmp/delta/delta-table")) Creating a table in SQL: Sometimes it can make sense to write in SQL. Run the following to create a Delta table with SQL: spark.sql(""" CREATE TABLE delta_table_sql (country STRING, continent STRING) USING delta
""") spark.sql(""" INSERT INTO delta_table_sql VALUES ('china', 'asia'), ('argentina', 'south america')
""").show You can continue programming in an SQL fashion, with a delta table instead of a table, but this tutorial will continue with Python.

14.body: The Delta Log is the transaction log of changes to tables in the Delta Lake. Through this log, all readers and writers have access to the "true" state of each table, even if tables have been modified since the last time they were read. Spark will check the log to see if new transactions are posted to a table and update the end user's table with any new changes. This allows atomicity, multiple concurrent reads and writes in addition to conflict resolution. The Delta Log enables us to run many of the key Delta lake's properties, like ACID transactions, scalable metadata handling, time travel, and more. Deep dive: - https://www.databricks.com/blog/2019/08/21/diving-into-delta-lake-unpacking-the-transaction-log.html - https://books.japila.pl/delta-lake-internals/DeltaLog/ See the _delta_log for the table! dbutils.fs.ls("/tmp/delta/delta-table") Display history of the table: display(spark.sql("DESCRIBE HISTORY delta.`/tmp/delta/delta-table`"))
14.title: The Delta Log

15.body:
With Time travel you can access older version of a table, with either a timestamp or version timestamp expression can be any one of: - '2018-10-18T22:15:12.013Z', that is, a string that can be cast to a timestamp - cast('2018-10-18 13:36:32 CEST' as timestamp) - '2018-10-18', that is, a date string - current timestamp() - interval 12 hours - date sub(current date(), 1) - Any other expression that is or can be cast to a timestamp version is a long value that can be obtained from the output of DESCRIBE HISTORY table_spec. Lets mess with the table. We will select windspeed and multiply all values with 100. temp_df = spark.read.format("delta").option("inferSchema","true").load("/tmp/delta/delta-table") temp_df = temp_df.withColumn("windspeed", temp_df.windspeed*100)
temp_df.write.format("delta").mode("overwrite").save("/tmp/delta/delta-table")
temp_df.show() Again, we look at the history of the delta table. Notice the new entry: display(spark.sql("DESCRIBE HISTORY delta.`/tmp/delta/delta-table`")) Copy one of the earlier entries in the timestamps column of the output of the last code cell and put it in timestamp_string. We will use it to read the corresponding data. timestamp_string = "2023-01-15T10:34:12.000+0000" #PUT YOUR TIMESTAMP HERE
df1 = spark.read.format("delta").option("timestampAsOf", timestamp_string).load("/tmp/delta/delta-table") df1.show() we accessed the version where Windspeed still had its original value! Now do the same but we use the first version of the table: display(spark.sql("DESCRIBE HISTORY delta.`/tmp/delta/delta-table`")) version = "0" df2 = spark.read.format("delta").option("versionAsOf", version).load("/tmp/delta/delta-table")
df2.show() Using this, for example, we can query the number of new entries from the last day or week, or since the last table version! Observe that the following code will not run since there is no history for the last week. see more: - https://docs.delta.io/latest/delta-batch.html#query-an-older-snapshot-of-a-table-time-travel # THIS CODE WILL NOT RUN
last_week = spark.sql("SELECT CAST(date_sub(current_date(), 7) AS STRING)").collect()[0][0]
df = spark.read.format("delta").option("timestampAsOf", last_week).load("/tmp/delta/delta-table")
last_week_count = df.select("instant").distinct().count()
count = spark.read.format("delta").load("/tmp/delta/events").select("instant").distinct().count()
new_customers_count = count - last_week_count

2.body: A Data Warehouse is a repository with structured data which supports Business Intelligence (BI) and analytic. Contents in a warehouse are preprocessed and organized, usually through ETL (Extract, Transform, Load) operations that feed into it. Warehouses provide reliability and ACID transactions , and have been a popular solution since the 1980's. A Data Lake is a central repository that stores all organizational data (unstructured, semistructed, or structured). A Data lake Architecture typically handles large volumes of raw data without the need to structure it first. Raw and unstructured Data stored in Data lakes can be used to build Data Pipelines , which is cover later on in the module. Data Lakes have been popular since 2011 with the availability of HDFS and low cost storage, including with services such as AWS S3 .
2.title: Data Warehouse vs Data Lake

3.body: Another important property of Delta Lake and Lakehouse Architecture is ACID guarantees . The term ACID stands for four key properties: - Atomicity : Means that all transactions (a single unit of work that accesses or modifies contents of a database) either succeed or fail completely. An action is either committed and changes are made visible, or a transaction is aborted and no changes are made. - Consistency : Data is in a consistent state when a transaction starts and ends. If there is a constraint in a database that bank balances must remain positive, a consistent transaction mantains this state if positive bank balances occur before and after the transaction. - Isolation : This property ensures that multiple transactions can occur concurrently without leading to inconsistency of the database state. Transactions should be run in an isolated environment without interfering with each other. - Durability : This property guarantees that changes are permitted once a transaction is completed. This ensures that data within a system persits in the case of failures and crashes. ACID transactions basically guarantee data validity despite errors and interruptions. In regards to Delta Lake and Lakehouses, when data is read and written simultaneously, it is important to keep data integrity. Delta Lake keeps track of all commits made to tables to keep data consistent accross multiple users.
3.title: ACID Guarantees

34.body: After the pipeline has been created and configured, you start an update . This will start the cluster, check for invalid table properties, syntax errors and missing dependencies. Then tables and views are updated. How tables and view are updated depends on the type of update: Refresh all will update all tables to the current state of their input data sources. For streaming live tables, only new rows are appended to the table . Full refresh all will do the same, except for streaming live tables, Delta Live Tables attempts to clear all data from each table then load all data from the streaming source. Refresh selection option is identical to refresh all, except it allows to refresh only selected tables, and other tables downstream in the pipeline will be updated in the process. Full refresh selection is identical to full refresh all on a selection of tables. This means that all data is refreshed, and streaming live tables will clear all data and load from the streaming source again.

https://docs.databricks.com/workflows/delta-live-tables/delta-live-tables-quickstart.html https://docs.databricks.com/workflows/delta-live-tables/delta-live-tables-sql-ref.html https://docs.databricks.com/workflows/delta-live-tables/delta-live-tables-data-sources.html This notebook demonstrates using Delta Live Tables Quickstart Pipeline on a dataset containing Wikipedia clickstream Databricks dataset. To create our initial live table called clickstream_raw: CREATE LIVE TABLE clickstream_raw
COMMENT "The raw wikipedia click stream dataset, ingested from /databricks-datasets."
AS SELECT * FROM json.`/databricks-datasets/wikipedia-datasets/data-001/clickstream/raw-uncompressed-json/2015_2_clickstream.json` CREATE LIVE TABLE clickstream_clean( CONSTRAINT valid_current_page EXPECT (current_page_title IS NOT NULL), CONSTRAINT valid_count EXPECT (click_count > 0) ON VIOLATION FAIL UPDATE
)
COMMENT "Wikipedia clickstream data cleaned and prepared for analysis."
AS SELECT curr_title AS current_page_title, CAST(n AS INT) AS click_count, prev_title AS previous_page_title
FROM live.clickstream_raw CREATE LIVE TABLE top_spark_referers
COMMENT "A table containing the top pages linking to the Apache Spark page."
AS SELECT previous_page_title as referrer, click_count
FROM live.clickstream_clean
WHERE current_page_title = 'Apache_Spark'
ORDER BY click_count DESC
LIMIT 10

In either iODBC or ODBC manager, create a DSN with the information provided below: dsn_setup You can get your Host and HTTPPath from the SQL warehouse settings, and put your authentication token as PWD . This token can be generated from the user settings page. With iODBC, you can optionally test the ODBC connection before connecting to Excel. Open iODBC Demo (Unicode) . In the toolbar, go to Environment and Open Connection . Choose the DSN we just created. Again, enter "token" as username and your databricks authentication token as password. In the toolbar, click SQL and then Execute SQL . Now we can try to query the database. We will query the china*matches table in the trase*pipelines schema. 53.body:
Delta sharing is useful for provides secure sharing of data with external parties. This is available in Databricks through the Unity Catalog , as well as in open source Delta.io . Resources: - https://docs.databricks.com/data-sharing/index.html - https://github.com/delta-io/delta-sharing The following code example is from the Delta sharing github . Through a generated and shared profile file, you access a "delta share" which consists of a selected number of tables with read only access to them. import delta_sharing # install with pip 'install delta-sharing' # Point to the profile file. It can be a file on the local file system or a file on a remote storage.
profile_file = "<profile-file-path>" # Create a SharingClient.
client = delta_sharing.SharingClient(profile_file) # List all shared tables.
client.list_all_tables() # Create a url to access a shared table.
# A table path is the profile file path following with `#` and the fully qualified name of a table # (`<share-name>.<schema-name>.<table-name>`).
table_url = profile_file + "#<share-name>.<schema-name>.<table-name>" # Fetch 10 rows from a table and convert it to a Pandas DataFrame. This can be used to read sample data # from a table that cannot fit in the memory.
delta_sharing.load_as_pandas(table_url, limit=10) # Load a table as a Pandas DataFrame. This can be used to process tables that can fit in the memory.
delta_sharing.load_as_pandas(table_url) # If the code is running with PySpark, you can use `load_as_spark` to load the table as a Spark DataFrame.
delta_sharing.load_as_spark(table_url)

6.body: Lakehouse architecture aims to provide the ACID guarantees and reliability of warehouses while only requiring the cost-effectiveness, efficiency and scalability that Data Lakes provide. Companies and organisations usually rely on warehouses for BI and analytics, while also needing raw data from Data lakes for applications such as machine learning, which can result in a more complex architecture, additional ETL processes, duplicate and stale data, as well as extra costs and vendor lock-in. If we can provide the structure and reliability of warehouses on top of a Data lake, we can ommit the need for the warehouse! This can be achieved with the help of metadata layers within the Data lake, which keep track of key information such as transactions (enabling versioning and ACID capabilities), and statistics of underlying structured data, in a similar way as a .git folder saves relevant information of a Git repository. Two examples that enable this are Delta Lakes or Apache Iceberg , both of which are currently based on Parquet files to store structured information in tabular format.

8.body: Delta Lake is an open-source table storage layer over cloud object stores initially developed at Databricks, and is designed to run on top of an existing Data Lake. It serves an integral part in the Databricks Lakehouse, and enables the following: ACID guarantees: as mentioned earlier, ACID guarantees is a higly regarded property. Data lakes typically have multiple data pipelines reading and writing concurrently. Scalable data and metadata handling: Metadata itself can grow to huge sizes within a Data lake. Audit history and time travel: Logs of transactions and audit history enables access to revert to earlier versions of data for audits or to reproduce experiments. Schema enforcement and schema evolution: This provides ability to both enforce schemas and allows changing schemas when needed Open format: All data in a Delta Lake is stored in Apache Parquet format , a file format designed to support fast data processing, with columnar based formats, allowing for higher performance when selecting and filtering data. More on parquet file format . Streaming and batch unification: Delta tables is both a batch table and a streaming source and sink. We can write both batch and streaming data into the same table. Note that Delta Lake (Delta.io) is open source, but the pipeline that will be run in later notebooks utilizes Databricks Delta Live Tables (DLT) that makes it easy to declaratively build and manage whole data pipelines on a Delta Lake. Deep dive into Lakehouse and Delta lake: Delta Lake: High-Performance ACID Table Storage over Cloud Object Stores - https://www.databricks.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/p975-armbrust.pdf Delta lake: The Definitive Guide by O’Reilly (in development) - https://www.databricks.com/p/ebook/delta-lake-the-definitive-guide-by-oreilly Lighter reading & video: The Databricks Lakehouse Platform - https://www.databricks.com/product/data-lakehouse Delta Lake 2.0 Overview (38m) - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VWJT3JyPKvk The Data Lakehouse Platform For Dummies - https://www.databricks.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/The-Data-Lakehouse-Platform-For-Dummies-1.pdf Oskar note 13/1 - 2023 if there is time, add some images or examples of delta lake being used in the real world, and maybe some references to its crazy performance in some use cases.

9.body: Delta Live Tables is an extension of delta tables in Databricks with extra functionalities, so its important not to remember the differences of Delta Lake, Delta Table and Delta Live Table. DLT is covered in its own notebooks, but for now, keep in mind that Delta Live Tables and the databricks pipeline they run in basically adds or simplifies some moments of setting up a data management pipeline, such as: Managed workflow for loading delta tables Dependency management Managing data expectations on data quality Visual interface for data lineage and analysis The next notebook will go specifically into Delta Lake and Delta Tables to set up some foundational knowledge on these topics. Later, we will delve more into Databricks Delta Live Tables and the Pipeline.
